in article <c5juyz.aly@murdoch.acc.virginia.edu> rws2v@uvacs.cs.virginia.edu (richard stoakley) writes: >	we need a good concave ->convex polygon conversion routine. >i've tried a couple without much luck. please e-mail responses and i >will post a summary of any replies. thank you. > >richard stoakley >rws2v@uvacs.cs.virginia.edu the problem is not precisely defined above, but if you need to find the smallest convex polygon that encloses a given polygon, then you are seeking the convex hull of your original polygon. there are two ways to do this: use a somewhat tricky but by-now well examined linear-time algorithm that exploits the polygon boundary, or just feed the vertices of the original polygon to a convex hull routine and accept o(n log n). both methods are discussed in preparata and shamos, for example.
