t from rome to be used if there were a problem with one of the primary objects) and items omitted later in the planning process. this exhibit will be of interest to medieval and renaissance scholars in particular, but also to art historians, historians of science or medicine, early music scholars, students of the humanist movement, students of printing and the printed word, theologians, scholars of both far and near eastern studies, and to librarians and information professionals. please get the readme file for details on what files this exhibit contains. if you have questions about how to use ftp, speak to your local computer support person. if you have questions or comments about the content of the exhibit, please write to vatican@kell.loc.gov while if you have any questions or comments on the system please contact me. -- k.d. ellis ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++ k.d. ellis special projects office library of congress washington, dc 20540-9100 internet: kell@seq1.loc.gov
